    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-12-19T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-12-19T23:00:00-05:00" n="405"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d405">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/14522: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-12-20T11:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 20, 1938—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 21—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>610. The Embassy learns from reliable sources that the Generalissimo at a
                    meeting, convoked on December 18, issued a forceful rebuke to the civil
                    officials of the National Government for what he termed their frivolous
                    attitude, inefficiency, corruption and waste in the face of a grave national
                    crisis and pointing to life being led by the soldiers in the field, strongly
                    admonished his listeners to be diligent, honest, eschew all amusements, and in
                    short to pull together with the army in the war. A statement worded in a similar
                    vein, and published in the local press, was issued by General Chen Cheng, close
                    collaborator of Chiang Kai Shek, on December 16.</p>
                <pb facs="0426" n="422" xml:id="pg_422"/>
                <p>It would appear that this move presages a “moral purge” of civil officialdom and
                    a reemphasizing of the tenets of the New Life movement.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
